<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-21T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-21T23:00:00-05:00" n="446" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d446">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/7: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-22T12:00:00+08:00">February 22,
                                1932—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received February 22—3 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>261. Following from American Consul General, Mukden.</p>
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“February 20, 6 p.m. According to a report of the Japanese press,
                                preparations for the establishment of the new state are being
                                carried out rapidly and its inauguration will occur at Changchun on
                                March 1st. The report also said that Changchun will be the capital
                                and that work on the buildings for the new government has been
                                started. It is reported <persName corresp="#p_PH1">Pu Yi</persName>
                                will be the President.”</p></quote>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>